ized, biomedicalized, and technological machine-one that frequently failed to serve the Chinese people. Mason grapples with how public health in China was reinvented into a prestigious profession in which global recognition took precedent over service to vulnerable local communities. This book lays bare the common elements of a global pandemic that too often get overlooked, all of which are being thrown into sharp relief during the present COVID-19 outbreak: blame of "exotic" customs from the country of origin and the poor bearing the most severe consequences. Mason's argument resonates profoundly with our current crisis, making the case that we can only consider ourselves truly prepared for the next crisis once public health policies, and social welfare more generally, are made more inclusive.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aPublic health administrationxChina, Southeast. 0aPublic health administrationzChina, Southeast. 0aPublic healthxChina, Southeast. 0aPublic healthzChina, Southeast. 0aSARS (Disease)xChina, SoutheastxChina, Southeast. 0aSARS (Disease)zChina, Southeast. 4aCDC. 4aChina. 4aSARS. 4abioethics. 4aglobal health. 4amigration. 4apandemics. 4aprofessionalization. 4apublic health. 4aurbanization. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Disease & Health Issues.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479895240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804798952423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804798952.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles